title: Georgia Open Records Act Request – January 17, 2024 Arrest of Tyree Chapman (Fleeing, Trash Can Arrest)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

copies of all video and audio recordings related to the arrest of Tyree Chapman on January 17, 2024, by the Atlanta Police Department and associated agencies.

Specifically, I request:

All body-worn camera footage from officers who pursued, located, or arrested Mr. Chapman.

All dashcam/in-car video footage related to this incident.

All video from the Aviation Unit (helicopter footage) showing Chapman’s vehicle, foot pursuit, and arrest.

Any surveillance or third-party footage reviewed or collected by APD.

Any 911 calls, dispatch audio, or radio communications related to the incident.

Identifying Details:

Name of Arrestee: Tyree Chapman

Date: January 17, 2024

Time: Approx. 3:37 PM to 4:00 PM EST (as shown in timestamped bodycam and aviation unit footage)

Initial Location: 300 block of Boulevard NE, Atlanta, GA

Vehicle Involved: Stolen Infiniti Q50 (black)

Pursuit Path: From Chevron gas station to Glenn Street SW and adjoining residential area

Arrest Location: In a trash can in a suburban neighborhood near the 300 block of Glenn Street SW

Charges: Fleeing to elude, reckless driving, firearm possession during felony, theft by receiving, and driving on suspended/revoked license

Notable Footage: Bodycam and aerial footage show Chapman hiding in a trash can; a handgun was found in a separate trash can nearby.

Please inform me of any fees prior to fulfilling this request. If any part of the materials are exempt from release, please provide the non-exempt portions and cite the applicable exemptions.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

title: Flock Safety search audits and data sharing (Largo PD)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Flock Safety search audits and data sharing (Largo, FL)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Search audits and data sharing records related to the agency’s Flock Safety system.

Search audits from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed, including:
- 1. Internal search audits -
Audit logs documenting each time a department account has conducted a search in the department's Flock Safety ALPR system from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. Flock Safety calls this an “Organization Audit.”

- 2. External search audits -
Audit logs documenting the searches by users/organizations from outside of the department, that included the department’s Flock Safety ALPR cameras, from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. Flock Safety calls this a “Network Audit.” 

Flock audit logs are retained indefinitely and contain metadata including, but not limited to: the date of the search, the time of the search, the search term/rules, cameras searched, and the user/organization conducting the search. The audit logs are recorded in a database so I ask that you please provide it to me as a .csv, .xls, or other database filetype.


Data sharing settings as of the date this request is processed including:
- 3. Networks that I’m sharing -
The names of agencies and organizations with which the Agency shares its Flock Safety ALPR data, also referred to as "Networks that I’m sharing."

- 4. Flock networks shared with me -
The names of agencies and organizations that have shared their cameras with the Agency, also referred to as "Flock networks shared with me."

The share settings are recorded in a database so I ask that you please provide it to me as a .csv, .xls, or other database filetype.

Correspondence – including calls (phone, Zoom and Microsoft Teams), texts, emails and messages – between the City of Fort Worth, (including Mayor Mattie Parker) and the USDA, (including Sec. of Agriculture Brooke Rollins) between 3/13/2025 and the date this request is received.

title: FOIA REQUEST - Animal Cruelty Case of Jordan Love

communications.subject: Michigan Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA REQUEST - Animal Cruelty Case of Jordan Love
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Michigan Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting access to and copies of public records pertaining to the animal cruelty investigation of Jordan Love, who has been charged by the Wayne County Prosecutor's Office following an investigation that involved both the Detroit Police Department (DPD) and Detroit Animal Care and Control (DACC).

The incident occurred on or around February 7, 2025, at a residence in the 15200 block of Manning Street, Detroit. This case involves the non-fatal stabbing of a dog, the dispatch of DACC officers to the scene at approximately 2:00 p.m. on February 7, 2025, and the seizure of three dogs and four cats from the residence.

To assist in your search, please consider this a request directed to both the Detroit Police Department and Detroit Animal Care and Control, and utilize the following details regarding the case:

- Suspect Name: Jordan Love
- Approximate Date of Incident: February 7, 2025
- Location of Incident: 15200 block of Manning Street, Detroit
- Nature of Incident: Non-fatal dog stabbing
- DACC Dispatch Time (approximate): 2:00 p.m. on February 7, 2025

I am specifically interested in obtaining the following types of records from both the Detroit Police Department and Detroit Animal Care and Control related to this case:

From the Detroit Police Department:

- Incident Reports related to the initial call and response.

- Investigation Files, including any reports, notes, and evidence collected.

- Witness Statements obtained during the investigation.

- Photographs taken at the scene or of the injured animal.

- Video Recordings, including any body camera footage from responding officers or surveillance footage obtained.

- All communication, reports, or information shared with Detroit Animal Care and Control regarding this incident.

- Records related to the apprehension and extradition of Jordan Love.

- Other Relevant Documents pertaining to the investigation of this case by the DPD.

From Detroit Animal Care and Control:

- Dispatch records related to the call on February 7, 2025, to the 15200 block of Manning Street.

- Animal Control Reports filed by the responding officers.

- Records pertaining to the seizure of the three dogs and four cats from the residence.

- Veterinary reports obtained by DACC for the injured dog.

- Intake records for all animals seized.
Disposition records for all animals seized (current status and placement, if applicable).

- Photographs or videos taken by Animal Control officers at the scene or of the animals.

- All communication, reports, or information shared with the Detroit Police Department regarding this incident.

- Witness statements collected by Animal Control officers.

- Other Relevant Documents pertaining to DACC's involvement in this case.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Colon

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Incident Records, Complaints, Audio/Video Evidence, and Disciplinary History Involving Officer Jackman (Badge #64), Officer Kreuscher (Badge #39), and Sergeant Franco
communications.communication:
Jordan Lassiter
Investigative Journalist
April 10, 2025

VIA EMAIL & FOIL PORTAL
Peekskill Police Department
Custodian of Records
2 Nelson Avenue
Peekskill, NY 10566
Email: FOIL@cityofpeekskill.com

DISCLAIMER:
This request is submitted under the New York Freedom of Information Law (FOIL), Article 6 of the Public Officers Law. All communications regarding this request may be shared publicly as part of a journalistic transparency initiative.

FREEDOM OF INFORMATION LAW REQUEST – Incident Records, Complaints, Audio/Video Evidence, and Disciplinary History Involving Officer Jackman (Badge #64), Officer Kreuscher (Badge #39), and Sergeant Franco

Dear FOIL Officer,

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law (Public Officers Law, Article 6), I, Jordan Lassiter, hereby request access to the following records relating to the conduct, internal oversight, complaint history, audiovisual documentation, and communications involving Officer Jackman (Badge #64), Officer Kreuscher (Badge #39), and Sergeant Franco of the Peekskill Police Department. This request is prompted by a specific incident involving these officers that occurred on or around December 4, 2024, and includes broader concerns regarding professional conduct.

In accordance with New York Public Officers Law § 84-90, and the prevailing interpretation of FOIL in relevant court decisions including Matter of Gould v. New York City Police Dept., 89 N.Y.2d 267 (1996), and Mulgrew v. Board of Educ. of City Sch. Dist. of City of N.Y., 87 A.D.3d 506 (1st Dept. 2011), the following records are requested:

Incident-Specific Records for December 4, 2024:
a. All body-worn camera footage, dash camera footage, surveillance video, or third-party video recordings involving or captured by Officer Jackman, Officer Kreuscher, and Sergeant Franco during the incident on December 4, 2024. Please indicate whether each device was activated, functional, and in compliance with departmental policy. (Gould, 89 N.Y.2d at 276, confirming public access to factual materials and recordings).
b. Any 911 audio recordings, CAD reports, dispatcher logs, or transcripts related to the December 4, 2024 incident. (Daily Gazette Co. v. City of Schenectady, 93 N.Y.2d 145 (1999), requiring disclosure of factual components of police records).
c. Any internal reports, use-of-force forms, narrative reports, affidavits, complaints, or supplemental documentation created in relation to the December 4, 2024 incident. (LaRocca v. Bd. of Educ. of City of Niagara Falls, 220 A.D.2d 1000 (4th Dept. 1995)).
d. Any text messages, emails, or other communications between officers or supervisors related to the incident, including informal channels (e.g., personal devices used in official capacity). (Matter of Tuck-It-Away Assoc., L.P. v. Empire State Dev. Corp., 54 A.D.3d 154 (1st Dept. 2008)).
e. Any disciplinary proceedings, administrative investigations, citizen or internal complaints, memos, command reviews, or findings related to the conduct of Officer Jackman, Officer Kreuscher, or Sergeant Franco during or in response to this incident. (Matter of New York Civ. Liberties Union v. New York City Police Dept., 32 N.Y.3d 556 (2018)).
f. Records indicating whether Officer Jackman failed to activate his body-worn camera, and any review of this action for policy violation or misconduct. (Matter of Prisoners' Legal Servs. of N.Y. v. New York State Dept. of Corr. & Community Supervision, 73 N.Y.S.3d 651 (3d Dept. 2018)).
g. Any complaints or statements alleging Officer Jackman used profane, disrespectful, or demeaning language toward citizens while in uniform during this incident, including any written or recorded civilian affidavits or statements. (Matter of Luongo v. Records Access Officer, Civilian Complaint Review Bd., 150 A.D.3d 13 (1st Dept. 2017)).

Officer Jackman (Badge #64):
a. A comprehensive list and summary of all civilian or internal complaints filed against Officer Jackman, whether sustained or not, including the nature of the allegations, complaint dates, and disciplinary outcomes. (Matter of New York Times Co. v. City of N.Y. Police Dept., 179 A.D.3d 556 (1st Dept. 2020)).
b. All disciplinary actions, counseling records, internal memos, and hearing transcripts involving Officer Jackman. (Gould, 89 N.Y.2d at 276).
c. Any video, audio, written testimony, or affidavits submitted in relation to previous disciplinary proceedings. (Luongo, 150 A.D.3d at 20).

Officer Kreuscher (Badge #39):
a. A summary of all civilian or internal complaints filed against Officer Kreuscher, including the nature of the allegations, incident dates, and outcomes. (Matter of Hearst Corp. v. State of N.Y. Police, 109 A.D.3d 32 (3d Dept. 2013)).
b. Any disciplinary actions, official reprimands, or findings of misconduct involving Officer Kreuscher. (Matter of Karlin v. McMahon, 96 N.Y.2d 842 (2001)).
c. Any body-worn camera footage or dash camera recordings from other incidents that were the subject of misconduct complaints involving Officer Kreuscher. (Matter of Daily Gazette Co.).

Sergeant Franco:
a. All civilian or internal complaints filed against Sergeant Franco, including allegations of supervisory misconduct, retaliation, dereliction of duty, or discriminatory behavior. (Matter of Police Benevolent Assn. of N.Y. State Troopers, Inc. v. State of N.Y., 11 N.Y.3d 96 (2008)).
b. All disciplinary records, findings, or hearings involving Sergeant Franco, including reprimands, suspensions, demotions, or administrative hearing documentation. (Gould, 89 N.Y.2d at 276).
c. All body-worn camera, dashcam, surveillance, or audio recordings involving Sergeant Franco during the December 4, 2024 incident or any incident tied to filed complaints. (Daily Gazette, 93 N.Y.2d at 151).
